    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "We have seen previously that a radical is a number expressed using the radical sign $\\sqrt{\\phantom{x}}$.\n\nIn particular, the square root of a number $a$ is the number which, when multiplied by itself, gives $a$. So, $\\sqrt{a} \\times \\sqrt{a} = a$.\n\nOPERATIONS WITH RADICALS",
      "source_images": ["image289.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 23\n\nSimplify:\n\n(a) $\\sqrt{11} \\times \\sqrt{11}$\n\n(b) $(\\sqrt{13})^2$\n\nAnswer\n\n(a) $\\sqrt{11} \\times \\sqrt{11} = 11$\n\n(b) $(\\sqrt{13})^2 = \\sqrt{13} \\times \\sqrt{13} = 13$",
      "source_images": ["image289.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 24\n\nSimplify:\n\n(a) $4\\sqrt{3} \\times \\sqrt{3}$\n\n(b) $(2\\sqrt{5})^2$\n\nAnswer\n\n(a) $4\\sqrt{3} \\times \\sqrt{3} = 4 \\times \\sqrt{3} \\times \\sqrt{3} = 4 \\times 3 = 12$\n\n(b) $(2\\sqrt{5})^2 = 2\\sqrt{5} \\times 2\\sqrt{5} = 2 \\times 2 \\times \\sqrt{5} \\times \\sqrt{5} = 4 \\times 5 = 20$",
      "source_images": ["image290.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "concept",
      "content_latex": "Radicals in simplest form can be 'collected' in the same way as 'like' algebraic terms.\n\nFor example, since $2x + 3x = 5x$,\n\n$2\\sqrt{2} + 3\\sqrt{2} = 5\\sqrt{2}$.",
      "source_images": ["image291.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 25\n\nSimplify:\n\n(a) $4\\sqrt{3} + 2\\sqrt{3}$\n\n(b) $3 + \\sqrt{2} + 4 - 5\\sqrt{2}$\n\nAnswer\n\n(a) $4\\sqrt{3} + 2\\sqrt{3} = 6\\sqrt{3}$\n\n(b) $3 + \\sqrt{2} + 4 - 5\\sqrt{2} = 7 - 4\\sqrt{2}$",
      "source_images": ["image291.png"]
    },
    {
      "type": "example",
      "content_latex": "Example 26\n\nExpand and simplify:\n\n(a) $\\sqrt{2}(\\sqrt{2} + 3)$\n\n(b) $3\\sqrt{3}(6 - 2\\sqrt{3})$\n\nAnswer\n\n(a) $\\sqrt{2}(\\sqrt{2} + 3) = \\sqrt{2} \\times \\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{2} \\times 3 = 2 + 3\\sqrt{2}$\n\n(b) $3\\sqrt{3}(6 - 2\\sqrt{3}) = 3\\sqrt{3} \\times 6 + 3\\sqrt{3} \\times (-2\\sqrt{3}) = 18\\sqrt{3} - 6 \\times 3 = 18\\sqrt{3} - 18$",
      "source_images": ["image292.png"]
    },
    {
